===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|nere}}, {{m|enm|ner|}}, from {{inh|en|ang|nēar|t=nearer|pos=comparative of {{m|ang|nēah|t=nigh}}}}, influenced by {{der|en|non|nær|t=near}}, both originating from {{der|en|gem-pro|*nēhwiz|t=nearer}}, comparative of the adverb {{m|gem-pro|*nēhw|t=near}}. Cognate with {{cog|ofs|niār|t=nearer}}, {{cog|nl|naar|t=to, towards}}, {{cog|de|näher|t=nearer}}, {{cog|da|nær|t=near, close}}, {{cog|no|nær|t=near, close}} {{cog|sv|nära|t=near, close}}. See also {{m|en|nigh}}.

''Near'' appears to be derived from (or at the very least influenced by) the North Germanic languages; compare {{cog|da|nær|t=near, close}}, {{cog|no|nær|t=near, close}} {{cog|sv|nära|t=near, close}}, as opposed to {{m|en|nigh}}, which continues the inherited West Germanic adjective, like {{cog|nl|na|t=close, near}}, {{cog|de|nah|t=close, near, nearby}}, {{cog|lb|no|t=nearby, near, close}}. Both, however, are ultimately derived from the same Proto-Germanic root: {{m|gem-pro|*nēhw|t=near, close}}.

